Learning Log
Day 1 вЂ” March 5, 2025
Topics: Basic types, function annotations, union types, type narrowing

Started with basic TypeScript syntax and type annotations. Practiced typing variables, function parameters, and return values. Also learned how union types work and how typeof helps narrow types.

Files: basicTypes.ts, functions.ts, unionTypes.ts, narrowing.ts

Day 2 вЂ” March 6, 2025
Topics: any, unknown, void, never, type assertions

Learned about different special types. One important takeaway was understanding why any should be avoided when possible and how unknown forces safer type checks. Also explored void, never, and basic type assertions.

Files: any.ts, unknown.ts, void.ts, never.ts, typeAssertions.ts

Day 3 вЂ” March 7, 2025
Topics: Objects, arrays, tuples, enums, optional/default params

Practiced defining types for objects and arrays. Tuples were a bit confusing at first since they look like arrays but enforce a fixed structure. Also experimented with enums and optional function parameters.

Files: objects.ts, arrays.ts, tuples.ts, enums.ts, functionsAdvanced.ts

Day 4 вЂ” March 9, 2025
Topics: Type aliases, interfaces, generics, typed API calls

Learned how type aliases and interfaces help organize complex types. Generics took some time to understand but made more sense when thinking of them as reusable type parameters. Also tried making a typed API request.

Files: typeAliases.ts, interfaces.ts, interfaceVsType.ts, generics.ts, apiTypes.ts, typedApiCall.ts

Day 5 вЂ” March 11, 2025
Topics: Using TypeScript with React components

Applied some of the fundamentals in a small React example. Created an interface for product data coming from an API, typed the component state, and built a small generic useFetch hook. Also tried utility types like Pick, Partial, and Omit while shaping object types.

This helped me see how the TypeScript concepts actually apply in real components.

Files: ProductList.tsx, useFetch.ts, StatusBanner.tsx, userTypes.ts



About
If you're also learning TypeScript, feel free to explore the examples. These files are mostly simple experiments while I learn and practice.

